{"topicId":"runtime-polymorphism-pointers","flashcards":[{"id":"fc-1","front":"What is a vtable and how does it enable runtime polymorphism?","back":"A vtable (Virtual Table) is a lookup table of function pointers created by the compiler for classes containing virtual functions. Each object with virtual functions contains a hidden pointer (vptr) to this table. When a virtual function is called via a base pointer, the runtime uses the vptr to look up the function address of the actual derived class object (Dynamic Dispatch), allowing polymorphic behavior."},{"id":"fc-2","front":"What is Object Slicing and how can it be prevented?","back":"Slicing occurs when a derived class object is passed by value to a function expecting a base class argument. The compiler uses the base class copy constructor, copying only the base portion and discarding the derived part.\n\n**Prevention:** Pass objects by reference or by pointer.\n```cpp\nvoid printInfo(Base& b) { b.show(); } // OK\nvoid printInfo(Base* b) { b->show(); } // OK\nvoid printInfo(Base b)  { b.show(); } // Slicing!```"},{"id":"fc-3","front":"Why is a virtual destructor necessary?","back":"If a base class destructor is not virtual and you delete a derived class object through a base class pointer, only the base destructor runs. This causes memory leaks for the derived class's allocated resources.\n\n```cpp\nclass Base { public: virtual ~Base() { cout << \"Base Dtor\"; } };\nclass Derived : public Base { public: ~Derived() { cout << \"Derived Dtor\"; } };\n\nBase* ptr = new Derived();\ndelete ptr; // Output: Derived Dtor -> Base Dtor\n```\nWithout `virtual`, only \"Base Dtor\" prints."},{"id":"fc-4","front":"What is a Pure Virtual Function and an Abstract Class?","back":"A Pure Virtual Function declares a virtual function in the base class with no implementation, forcing derived classes to provide one. Syntax: `virtual void render() = 0;`.\n\nA class containing at least one pure virtual function becomes an **Abstract Class**. You cannot instantiate an abstract class (e.g., `Shape s;` is illegal), but you can have pointers/references to it."},{"id":"fc-5","front":"How do you achieve Runtime Polymorphism using pointers?","back":"By declaring a pointer (or reference) of the base class type that points to an object of the derived class. The function called is determined by the object's actual type at runtime.\n\n```cpp\nclass Animal { public: virtual void speak() = 0; };\nclass Dog : public Animal { public: void speak() { cout << \"Woof\"; } };\n\nAnimal* a = new Dog();\na->speak(); // Calls Dog::speak() at runtime\n```"},{"id":"fc-6","front":"What is the purpose of the `override` specifier?","back":"The `override` keyword (C++11) ensures that a derived class function overrides a virtual function in the base class. It causes a compile-time error if the function signature does not match exactly, preventing accidental overloading or name hiding.\n\n```cpp\nclass Base { virtual void foo(int); };\nclass Derived : public Base {\n    void foo(int) override { } // Correct\n    // void foo(double) override { } // COMPILATION ERROR\n};\n```"},{"id":"fc-7","front":"How do you safely downcast polymorphic pointers?","back":"Use `dynamic_cast<Type*>(pointer)`. It checks the object's type at runtime (RTTI). If the cast is valid, it returns a valid pointer; if not, it returns `nullptr`.\n\n```cpp\nBase* b = new Derived();\nDerived* d = dynamic_cast<Derived*>(b);\nif (d) { d->derivedMethod(); }\n```\nNote: Requires at least one virtual function in the hierarchy."},{"id":"fc-8","front":"What is a pitfall with Virtual Functions and Default Arguments?","back":"Default argument values are resolved based on the **static type** (the pointer type), not the dynamic type (the actual object type). If a derived class overrides a function but doesn't specify the default argument, the base class default is used.\n\n```cpp\nclass Base { public: virtual void draw(int x=10) { cout << x; } };\nclass Der : public Base { public: void draw(int x=20) { cout << x; } };\n\nBase* b = new Der();\nb->draw(); // Prints 10 (The Base default), not 20!\n```"}]}